module.exports={homepage:{intro:{title:"The Rivalry Issue TMD",subtitle:"A collaboration between The Michigan Daily and The Lantern",paragraph:"Text for the introduction"}},michigan:[{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"influenza_pandemic_michigan_ohio_state_1918"},{type:"title",value:"How Michigan and Ohio State played through the last pandemic"},{type:"author",value:"Ethan Sears"},{type:"description",value:"Despite the influenza pandemic and World War I, Michigan and Ohio State played in front of 7,000 fans in 1918."},{type:"date",value:"December 10"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-10.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"During the last major pandemic, the Michigan football team had three of its former players killed in World War I. It had three games canceled as a result of influenza and wartime travel restrictions, two of the replacements for those games canceled and two more games — including Ohio State — rescheduled."},{type:"text",value:"And still, the Wolverines played the Buckeyes on the final Saturday of the season. They won, 14-0, to finish the year 5-0 — good enough to retroactively declare a national championship, but not good enough to beat Illinois in the polls for the Big Ten championship at the time. Due to the constant whir of games, the Illini had more conference wins, despite having lost a game."},{type:"text",value:'According to the <a href="https://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/aag4364.1919.001/525?page=root;size=100;view=image;q1=michiganensian">Michiganensian’s yearbook</a>, that was enough to keep “western writers” from giving Michigan a conference title.'},{type:"text",value:"In that sense, this pandemic is a full 180. The Michigan-Ohio State game won’t be played for the first time since 1917. The Buckeyes, despite having played fewer games than a one-loss Indiana, the team behind them in the standings, will play for the Big Ten title after the conference changed the rules to accommodate their 5-0 record."},{type:"text",value:"And, like Michigan in 1918, Ohio State would have come into The Game as prohibitive favorites. Whether the Wolverines would have kept it within two touchdowns, well, that’s another question."},{type:"text",value:'“The Buckeyes played a game which brought no criticism from the stands,” <a href="http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Olive/APA/Ohio/default.aspx#panel=document">The Lantern wrote</a> in its recap of the 1918 game, “because it was evident that they battled with every ounce of strength to ward off a tally and a possible defeat.”'},{type:"text",value:'Between The Lantern, <a href="https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071755693/281">The Michigan Daily</a>, <a href="https://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=8949845&fcfToken=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJmcmVlLXZpZXctaWQiOjExODYyMDAxMCwiaWF0IjoxNjA3NjM5MjcxLCJleHAiOjE2MDc3MjU2NzF9.f1_QSynAzQyOQwGEBYFX7Hgw0HBzGY-xXGR95AIbNf4">The Detroit Free Press</a> and the Michiganensian, the impact of the influenza pandemic on the game — played in front of 7,000 fans at a 14,000-capacity Ohio Field — scarcely draws mention.'},{type:"text",value:"Instead, much of the recaps focus on the heroics of Michigan lineman Angus Goetz, an All-Conference selection in 1918, and the impact of the win on the conference title. Goetz broke a scoreless gridlock by blocking an Ohio State punt with roughly 11:30 to go in the game. With the Buckeyes punting from their own 3-yard line, all he had to do was fall on the ball in the end zone to give Michigan its first points."},{type:"text",value:"The ensuing Ohio State drive ended in an interception. That helped set up the Wolverines with field position, and five minutes later, fullback Frank Steketee hit left end Robert Dunne for a 15-yard touchdown. It was one of few forward passes in the game."},{type:"text",value:"“Today’s game is entirely satisfactory,” former Michigan coach Fielding Yost said, according to The Daily. “Many of the players showed more than I thought was in them.”"},{type:"text",value:"It didn’t take long for the argument to begin."},{type:"text",value:"Alongside a Michigan-centric graphic on the front page of the sporting-financial section of the Free Press, Harry Bullion declared in his lede that, “If comparative scores are sound basis for determining the relative strength of the elevens, the Maize and Blue is at least the equal of the Champaign, Ill. delegation.”"},{type:"text",value:"Illinois refused an invitation from Michigan to play a defacto Big Ten championship game, citing cold weather as an excuse. The Wolverines were retroactively declared national champions by the Billingsley Report and the National Championship Foundation, with some historians citing them as co-Big Ten champions."},{type:"text",value:"Refutation for the latter, though, came from no less a source than Fielding Yost."},{type:"text",value:"“We would have been glad to have a postseason game with Illinois,” Yost said, per The Daily. “That is the only way that the real title could be settled, but since (Illinois) has already claimed the title, we will not contest it.”"}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"sports-monday-covid-game-excitement"},{type:"title",value:"COVID-19 may cancel The Game. It’s already canceled the excitement."},{type:"author",value:"Theo Mackie"},{type:"description",value:"Even with Ohio State being heavy favorites, The Game carries a certain air of excitement and expectation. This year, that week of infinite hope is gone because of COVID-19."},{type:"date",value:"December 7"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-9.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"It’s Monday morning of the week Michigan is scheduled to play Ohio State and there won’t be an unruly mess of TV cameras swarming Jim Harbaugh’s press conference. Even in this Zoom year, there won’t be four screens of reporters pining for that perfect soundbyte."},{type:"text",value:"On Twitter, there won't be fans performing the requisite mental gymnastics to convince themselves that this is the year the Wolverines finally win. There won’t be players saying they came to Michigan to beat Ohio State or seniors praying their last shot comes to fruition."},{type:"text",value:"The reason, of course, is a COVID-19 outbreak in the Michigan program that has put in-person practices on pause since last Monday and forced the cancelation of the Wolverines’ game against Maryland. Now, it’s threatening to cancel The Game."},{type:"text",value:"“It is disheartening that we’re not gonna be able to play Maryland,” athletic director Warde Manuel said last week in a video released to media. “And our hope is that we can play Ohio State and finish the season in the final week.”"},{type:"text",value:"Consider that for a second and let it sink in. For the first time in 103 years, Michigan might not play Ohio State. The last time it happened, there was the small matter of a World War. A year later, despite the Spanish flu pandemic limiting the Wolverines to five games, the two teams faced off at Ohio Field, with Michigan winning, 14-0."},{type:"text",value:"Let’s not have any misconceptions: That result is incredibly unlikely to happen this year, even if The Game is played. As of Sunday night, the Buckeyes are favored by 29.5 — a fair line considering one team is bound for the College Football Playoff and the other is 2-4."},{type:"text",value:"But despite this horrendous year for Harbaugh and Michigan, there’s something inconceivable about The Game being canceled — an outcome that seems more likely with each passing day."},{type:"text",value:"From a purely fact-based analysis of the rivalry’s last 15 years, a cancelation would seem to be no great loss. Since 2004, the Wolverines have won just once. Under Harbaugh, Michigan is 0-5. For nearly two decades, it hasn’t mattered whether the Wolverines are a national title contender or bottom-feeding fodder. They do nothing but alternate losses in Columbus with losses in Ann Arbor."},{type:"text",value:"And yet, there’s something impossibly hopeful about The Game. Think about the age-old debate amongst fans: Would Michigan rather finish 11-1 with a loss to Ohio State or 1-11 with a win over Ohio State? As foolish as the question is (and yes, 11-1 is the answer), it highlights the meaning of this game. A few lucky bounces and questionable calls can reverse a season’s lasting feeling."},{type:"text",value:"Consider, for example, the Buckeyes’ 2018 upset of Michigan. Ranked 10th in the country, they weren’t going to the College Football Playoff. By their sky-high standards, the season should have already been a disappointment. But they spoiled the Wolverines’ Revenge Tour party. That, not its eventual Rose Bowl win, is Ohio State’s lasting impression of its 2018 season."},{type:"text",value:"And if you think the same can’t happen for Michigan, think back a year further. With three losses before The Game and John O’Korn under center, the Wolverines were 12-point underdogs and had precious little to play for. Yet, they scored the game’s first 14 points, and led midway through the third quarter. Had Josh Metellus held onto a dropped second-quarter interception, Michigan likely would have won."},{type:"text",value:"Do I think that would happen this year if The Game is played? No. If I had to pick one side of Vegas’ 29.5-point spread, it’d be the Buckeyes’. But for these next five days, hope could at least emanate."},{type:"text",value:"“We still have the big team, OSU, at the end of the year,” senior offensive lineman Andrew Stueber said, when asked what Michigan had left to play for after a 27-17 loss to Penn State dropped the Wolverines to 2-4. “We just need to click on all cylinders and we’re in contention for that game.”"},{type:"text",value:"Call that a fairy tale impression of Michigan’s chances. I won’t blame you, because I agree. But the pure presence of that word — <em>chance</em> — matters. It matters to these players and it matters to Harbaugh."},{type:"text",value:"And if nothing else positive could have come out of this wretched year, they deserved those five days of annual optimism. It might be all they have."},{type:"text",value:"<em>Mackie can be reached at </em><em>tmackie@umich.edu</em><em> or on Twitter @theo_mackie.</em>"}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"schembechler-1969-upset"},{type:"title",value:"Schembechler leads Michigan to 1969 upset of No. 1 Ohio State"},{type:"author",value:"Daniel Dash"},{type:"description",value:"In Bo Schembechler’s first season, Michigan beat the top-ranked Buckeyes — arguably the best college football team ever assembled."},{type:"date",value:"Nov. 22, 1969"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-8.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"The Michigan football team’s 1969 upset of No. 1 Ohio State is, by all accounts, one of the biggest upsets in the history of college football."},{type:"text",value:"Reigning national champions at the time, the undefeated Buckeyes arrived in Ann Arbor after steamrolling through the first three months of their schedule. Ohio State had not trailed at any point during the 1969 season leading up to its showdown against the Wolverines. Legendary coach Woody Hayes had assembled one of the most talented teams in the sport’s history, as three Buckeyes finished in the top 10 of the 1969 Heisman Trophy voting."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State hadn’t scored fewer than 34 points in a game and its narrowest margin of victory came in a 34-7 drubbing of Minnesota. College football ran through Columbus."},{type:"text",value:"On the other side, first-year coach Bo Schembechler was attempting to save No. 12 Michigan from itself. The Wolverines were once among the country’s elite programs, but they had won only one Big Ten title in the 18 years prior to Schembechler’s arrival. During the previous season, Michigan lost by five touchdowns to the Buckeyes."},{type:"text",value:"When Schembechler was hired, he made his chief goal clear. The Wolverines were going to beat Ohio State under his watch."},{type:"text",value:"And in front of a record-setting crowd of 103,588 at Michigan Stadium in 1969, that’s exactly what his team did. Michigan stunned the Buckeyes, 24-12, ending Ohio State’s bid for a national title repeat and igniting the Ten Year War."},{type:"text",value:"“It may sound funny, but we knew before we went out there that we were going to win,” Wolverines’ safety Tom Curtis said after the game."},{type:"text",value:"According to a Michigan Daily story from Nov. 23, 1969, Schembechler was responsible for instilling that belief. He visited each player’s room the night before the game to tell them Ohio State’s players were not “Supermen.”"},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes, however, took immediate control of the game. They marched into the red zone on each of their first two possessions, sandwiched by a Michigan three-and-out. Ohio State converted an early opportunity into a touchdown, but the Wolverines answered with a successful run game."},{type:"text",value:"Michigan racked up 267 rushing yards on the afternoon. The Wolverines ran the ball 66 times, compared to just 20 pass attempts — a staple of their gameplan."},{type:"text",value:"“We planned to just run right at them,” Michigan offensive lineman Dan Dierdorf said. “Everybody else has panicked and come out throwing, not playing their own game.”"},{type:"text",value:"Michigan’s strong first half made a statement that redefined the entire rivalry. The Wolverines put up 17 points in the second quarter alone and took a 24-12 lead into the halftime locker room. Michigan’s defense finished the job, and the Buckeyes were held scoreless in the second half."},{type:"text",value:"As the clock hit zero, the ABC broadcast called it the “upset of the century.”"},{type:"text",value:"For Schembechler, the win was sweetened by his personal relationship with Hayes. He played for Hayes during his time at Miami (Ohio) before serving on his Ohio State staff, and after six years coaching his alma mater, Schembechler burst onto the scene of “The Game” in 1969."},{type:"text",value:"“We got outplayed and outpunched,” Hayes said."},{type:"text",value:"But on the other sideline, a legend was born."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"desmond-howard-pose"},{type:"title",value:"In 1991, Desmond Howard made the pose heard ‘round the world"},{type:"author",value:"Aria Gerson"},{type:"description",value:"In 1991, Desmond Howard’s iconic Heisman pose after a punt return touchdown"},{type:"date",value:"December 2"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-1.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"Desmond Howard is originally from Cleveland, deep in scarlet and gray territory. Before his final game against Ohio State, he made his friends back home a promise."},{type:"text",value:"“I told my friends from Ohio that if I got in the end zone against Ohio State, I’d do something special for them,” he said after the game."},{type:"text",value:"Then, late in the first half, it happened. Howard fielded a punt, easily dodged through several defenders, ran untouched into the end zone with his hands up and quickly struck the Heisman pose. It was an act of sheer arrogance — though one that was later justified when Howard did indeed win the Heisman Trophy."},{type:"text",value:"Michigan coach Gary Moeller didn’t see the pose at the time — the TV cameras caught it up close — and didn’t even believe it when he was told, going as far as to say, “One of my players would not do that.”"},{type:"text",value:"The pose is now firmly nestled in college football lore and still echoes far beyond Ann Arbor. Plenty of public figures now strike the Heisman pose just as Howard did back then."},{type:"text",value:"Many familiar faces took part in the 1991 Game, including Tyrone Wheatley Sr. and Chris Hutchinson for Michigan — both of whom later had sons play for Michigan — and now-ESPN commentator Kirk Herbstreit, who has called plenty of future iterations of The Game. (Herbstreit was knocked out of the 1991 game on a roughing the passer penalty and would quarterback the Buckeyes to a 13-13 tie the next year.)"},{type:"text",value:"While the ‘90s iterations of The Game were generally exciting and competitive, the 1991 Game was one of the least exciting of the bunch. The outcome was never in doubt, with Michigan (favored coming in at No. 4 to Ohio State’s No. 18) winning, 31-3, its fourth-straight win over the Buckeyes. Howard’s Heisman pose wasn’t the only time Michigan got style points, though. With the game still scoreless and the Wolverines on Ohio State’s 3-yard line, Moeller opted for a fake field goal shovel pass and converted the first down, going on to score a touchdown on the drive. From there, Michigan never looked back."},{type:"text",value:"“I thought it would be closer,” Michigan guard Matt Ellison said at the time. “ … I don’t think they played as well as some of the games we had seen on film.”"},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines’ win clinched them a spot in the Rose Bowl, which they (as per tradition) lost. Michigan finished the season 10-2 with a Big Ten title, its fourth of five consecutive Big Ten titles."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes, meanwhile, went to the Hall of Fame Bowl (now the Outback Bowl) in Tampa, Fla., which they lost to Syracuse, finishing 8-4 and third in the Big Ten."},{type:"text",value:"After the game, Howard provided some intrigue by claiming, “I think I’ll definitely be back” at Michigan, but it turned out not to be true. Howard declared for the draft that year and was selected fourth overall by Washington."},{type:"text",value:"Maybe it’s only appropriate that the Heisman pose was among the final moments of Howard’s Michigan career. In 1991, Howard was a consensus All-American, set school records for single-season touchdowns and points and even set a Big Ten record for single-season receiving touchdowns that still stands."},{type:"text",value:"The pose was one indelible moment that perfectly represented all his accolades, his own little piece of history and the one moment — more than the records — that people will always remember."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"1993-upset-win"},{type:"title",value:"In 1993, an improbable win kept Ohio State out of Pasadena"},{type:"author",value:"Aria Gerson"},{type:"description",value:"In 1993, a four-loss Michigan team pulled the upset over No. 5 Ohio State, keeping the Buckeyes out of the Rose Bowl."},{type:"date",value:"December 4"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-6.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"John Cooper called it one of the most embarrassing losses of his coaching career."},{type:"text",value:"After the game, the Wolverines lifted Gary Moeller onto their shoulders, carrying him off the field in front of a then-NCAA record 106,867 fans. It was one of the rivalry’s more stunning moments — a mediocre Michigan team that finished fifth in the Big Ten not only beating the fifth-ranked Buckeyes, but shutting them out, 28-0. One of the headlines in that Monday’s edition of The Daily? “Blue’s big plays bring ruin upon sputtering Bucks.”"},{type:"text",value:"The 1993 Wolverines had four losses already going into The Game — to Notre Dame, Michigan State, Illinois and Wisconsin. Ohio State, meanwhile, was undefeated with a lone tie."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State quarterback Bret Powers was intercepted three times, including twice by cornerback Ty Law. The Buckeyes’ punter also accidentally put his knee down handling a low snap in the third quarter, leading to ideal field position for Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"“We feel like we let everybody down,” Ohio State defensive lineman Dan Wilkinson said after the game. “Which we did.”"},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines’ offense wasn’t overpowering. Michigan’s longest drive consisted of six plays, and all but one were fewer than 50 yards. Tyrone Wheatley led the team in rushing with 105 yards but left the game early with a concussion. The Wolverines’ top receiver, Derrick Alexander, had just three catches for 64 yards."},{type:"text",value:"The defense, though, was another story. Nicknamed the “Lynch Mob,” the Wolverines’ secondary was chock full of talent but had disappointed most of the season. That wasn’t the case in The Game — in addition to the three interceptions, Michigan had four pass breakups. It was the Wolverines’ first shutout in two years and the Buckeyes’ first time being shut out since 1982. It is still the most recent shutout in the rivalry."},{type:"text",value:"“I pretty much knew what route they were going to run,” Law said after the game. “And I just played the ball when they threw it.”"},{type:"text",value:"Overall, 1993 was a forgettable year for Michigan. Leading up to the season, the Wolverines had won five consecutive Big Ten titles and six in seven years, along with five Rose Bowl appearances. By Thanksgiving 1993, they were out of contention for both — but that didn’t stop them from taking a wrecking ball to Ohio State’s season."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes would’ve locked up a Rose Bowl berth had they won in Ann Arbor. Instead, they had to settle for a shared conference title with Wisconsin, which got the spot in Pasadena because Ohio State had been there more recently. Michigan, meanwhile, finished its season in the Hall of Fame Bowl in Tampa, where it blew out NC State."},{type:"text",value:"That 1993 game was a vestige of the days of the rivalry in which either team could win any year, no matter the records. That era wouldn’t last much longer — the Wolverines have defeated the Buckeyes just twice since 2001."},{type:"text",value:"The lingering question for the 1993 Michigan team is what could have been had it played like it did against Ohio State in every game. The talent on that team was fully capable of beating anybody, but it just didn’t come together on a weekly basis."},{type:"text",value:"It was a missed opportunity for the Wolverines and they knew it, but at least the end of the season came with the ultimate prize."},{type:"text",value:"As The Daily put it at the time: “Oh, what a day.”"}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"charles-woodson-national"},{type:"title",value:"Michigan reached its modern-day peak with 1997 win"},{type:"author",value:"Theo Mackie"},{type:"description",value:"Heading into the 1997 iteration of The Game, No. 1 Michigan needed a win over No. 4 Ohio State to make the Rose Bowl and keep its National Championship hopes alive. The Wolverines did just that, defeating the Buckeyes, 20-14, en route to their first title in 49 years."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-2.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"“It just doesn’t get any better than this.”"},{type:"text",value:"That’s what Charles Woodson told reporters on Nov. 22, 1997, when No. 1 Michigan beat No. 4 Ohio State, 20-14. A month later, though, it did. The Wolverines kicked off 1998 with a 21-16 win over No. 8 Washington State, giving the program its first national title in 49 years."},{type:"text",value:"But it was on that Saturday in late November when Michigan made its greatest mark. In the final year before the BCS National Championship Game was implemented, the Wolverines could not afford to slip up. Undefeated Florida State and Nebraska loomed on their heels in the AP poll."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes, meanwhile, posed a dangerous threat, even with just one win over Michigan in the prior decade. Their sole loss on the season had come by four points at then-No. 2 Penn State a month prior."},{type:"text",value:"“They say paybacks are a mother and there will be some paybacks Saturday,” Ohio State linebacker Kevin Johnson promised before the game."},{type:"text",value:"On campus, the mood carried an air unrivaled in recent memory, with Michigan on the verge of its first undefeated season since 1971."},{type:"text",value:"In the pregame edition of The Daily, Nicholas Cotsonika wrote, “Anyone who sells their ticket to this game — for no other reason than making a personal profit — should withdraw from school. Now.”"},{type:"text",value:"A day later, those sellers were likely wishing they had heeded Cotsonika’s advice. By the middle of the third quarter, the Wolverines led, 20-0. An Anthony Thomas run opened the scoring, before Charles Woodson’s evaded seven Buckeyes, sending four of them flying to the turf on his famous second-quarter punt return. Andre Weathers’ pick-six finished off the early damage."},{type:"text",value:"“Never before has a Michigan team been this good, this talented, this determined and this well-coached,” John Leroi wrote in the Nov. 24 edition of The Daily. “The Wolverines have suited up for 119 years — and this is the best football team the school has ever fielded.”"},{type:"text",value:"First, though, Michigan had to hold off a final Buckeyes’ push."},{type:"text",value:"Three drives after Weathers’ pick-six, Ohio State quarterback Joe Germaine connected with receiver David Boston for a 56-yard score. The play accounted for over half of Germaine’s 84 passing yards on a day when the combination of the Wolverines’ stifling defense and a cold wintry mix held the Buckeyes to nine completions on 26 pass attempts."},{type:"text",value:"They didn’t fare much better on the ground, either, with 2.9 yards per carry on 41 attempts. It was that ground game, though, that brought Ohio State within six points with 13 minutes remaining after a fumble by Michigan quarterback Brian Griese gave the Buckeyes the ball at the Wolverines’ two-yard line."},{type:"text",value:"From there, Michigan clamped down, holding Ohio State to 20 yards of offense for the rest of the afternoon. And while the Buckeyes trudged to a Sugar Bowl consolation prize after their fifth-straight loss in Ann Arbor, the Wolverines broke a four-year Rose Bowl drought, with national championship aspirations intact."},{type:"text",value:"“When you start coaching, that’s always on the back of your mind,” Michigan coach Lloyd Carr said of national championship aspirations after the game."},{type:"text",value:"Added Griese: “I haven’t achieved my dream yet. I didn’t come back not to win the Rose Bowl. That was my goal from the start.”"},{type:"text",value:"A month later, the Wolverines did just that. Their 1997 season would forever be commemorated in newspaper clippings, photographs and unbreakable memories around the state."},{type:"text",value:"And Woodson’s proclamation still rings true. It would never “get any better than this” for a program that has spent 23 years aiming to rekindle 1997’s magic."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"2006-game-of-the-century"},{type:"title",value:"Michigan’s 2006 loss ended its best chance to return to the National Championship"},{type:"author",value:"Theo Mackie"},{type:"description",value:"In 2006, Michigan was only nine years removed from its most recent national title. Heading to The Game at 11-0, the Wolverines seemed destined to repeat. But after a loss in The Game of the Century, Michigan hasn’t been the same since."},{type:"date",value:"December 3"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-5.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"Ten years before The Spot, there was The Game of the Century."},{type:"text",value:"Like the 2016 matchup, it would chart the course of The Game for years to come. In the 13 years since, Michigan has won just once. Between Nov. 18, 2006 and the day Rich Rodriguez was fired in 2011, the Wolverines went 24-28. In the same span, the Buckeyes won five conference championships, played in two BCS National Championships and won a Rose Bowl."},{type:"text",value:"But when Lloyd Carr led Michigan into Ohio Stadium that Saturday in November, the Wolverines were on top of the college football world."},{type:"text",value:"It was a showdown that epitomized everything that worked about the much-maligned BCS. Both teams entered The Game 11-0. In the AP Poll, the Buckeyes reigned supreme over No. 2 Michigan. In the BCS, the spots were reversed."},{type:"text",value:"Today, both would have been destined for the College Football Playoff. But in 2006, only one was likely to survive with its National Championship hopes intact. The stakes were so momentous that The Daily’s Friday headline read only, “Tomorrow.” That was all that needed to be said."},{type:"text",value:"But then, on Friday morning, the only news that could have distracted from The Game broke: Legendary Michigan coach Bo Schembechler had died of a heart attack at age 77. Monday’s paper would feature a six-page tribute to Schembechler."},{type:"text",value:"The Game’s importance, though, was such that it still dominated Monday’s front page. “The one that got away,” was the front-page headline. “Second to one,” the Sports section cover read."},{type:"text",value:"After Michigan’s 42-39 loss, there was no other way to describe it. The Wolverines had let their best chance at a National Championship in nine years slip away."},{type:"text",value:"For Michigan, an early 7-0 lead evaporated far too quickly. By the middle of the second quarter, Ohio State had responded with three unanswered touchdowns, establishing a lead it would never relinquish."},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines closed the deficit to 28-24 with 8:41 left in the third quarter, but its defense couldn’t provide the requisite respite to complete the comeback."},{type:"text",value:"“We gave up too many big plays,” Carr said. “Any time you give up two long runs and a long pass, it’s going to be hard to beat anybody, much less a team like we played (Saturday). Big plays simply were the biggest factor in the game.”"},{type:"text",value:"One of those big plays — a 56-yard touchdown run — put the Buckeyes up 11 mid-way through the third quarter. From there, it was a seesaw of alternating touchdowns."},{type:"text",value:"And when Ohio State ran for one final first down late in the fourth quarter, time finally ran out on the Wolverines’ comeback dreams."},{type:"text",value:"“It meant everything to us,” running back Mike Hart said. “We lost. That’s the only thing.”"},{type:"text",value:"For a few fleeting days after The Game, Michigan’s National Championship hopes remained intact. In that week’s BCS rankings, the Wolverines remained ahead of one-loss USC and Florida teams."},{type:"text",value:"But when USC defeated Notre Dame the following week, Michigan dropped to third. The Trojans fell to UCLA the week after that, but the Gators surpassed the Wolverines by beating Arkansas in the SEC Championship Game."},{type:"text",value:"The day after the final BCS rankings were released, with Michigan .01 points behind Florida, the Daily’s Sports section headline read, “B-S?” The cover story questioned the BCS’ ranking, while ESPN analyst Kirk Herbstreit accused voters of simply not wanting a rematch."},{type:"text",value:"A month later, though, the BCS was validated. Florida crushed Ohio State, 41-14, to claim the National Championship. In the Rose Bowl, Michigan fell to USC, 32-18."},{type:"text",value:"Fourteen years later, the Wolverines haven’t made it back."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"2011-michigan-last-win-ohio-state"},{type:"title",value:"In 2011, a fleeting memory of victory for Michigan"},{type:"author",value:"Ethan Sears"},{type:"description",value:"When Brady Hoke’s Michigan beat Ohio State in his first year as head coach, it seemed like the start of something. Instead, it was Hoke’s peak."},{type:"date",value:"December 5"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-7.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"In the moment, it seemed like the start of something."},{type:"text",value:"Brady Hoke had broken a seven-year losing streak against Ohio State, given Michigan its first 8-0 record at home since 1927 when Michigan Stadium opened, taken the Wolverines to a New Year’s Six bowl they went on to win."},{type:"text",value:"The joy spilled onto the field as fans rushed it and tears welled in the eyes of the Michigan football team."},{type:"text",value:"“To be honest with you, I was numb,” fifth-year senior wide receiver Junior Hemingway said of his emotions after Courtney Avery’s game-clinching interception. “I didn’t know what to do.”"},{type:"text",value:"“I want to be nowhere else except with these guys,” junior quarterback Denard Robinson said. “I’m glad I stayed.”"},{type:"text",value:"“I got the best job in the world,” Hoke said."},{type:"text",value:"It turns out, a lone 40-34 win over Ohio State would be the highlight of his tenure in Ann Arbor."},{type:"text",value:"It turns out that, in looking back on the game recaps and newspaper clippings from the next days, what stands out the most is the name of one Urban Meyer, already connected with the Ohio State job. He’d soon replace interim coach Luke Fickell and lead the Buckeyes out of the scandal that mired that 2011 season, to an undefeated 2012, a national championship 2015, a second College Football Playoff appearance in 2017 and seven straight victories over Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Still, that day remains Michigan’s fondest memory in a decade of disappointment. Despite eventually finishing 6-7, Ohio State wouldn’t make things easy."},{type:"text",value:"Quarterback Braxton Miller hit a 54-yard touchdown pass on the Buckeyes’ opening drive and they went into the halftime locker room up 24-23. After the Wolverines retook the lead to open the second half, Ohio State would pull within three points not once, but twice."},{type:"text",value:"And when Michigan failed to pull away, settling for a 43-yard field goal that brought its lead to six with 1:59 left, the Buckeyes had a chance to win it."},{type:"text",value:"Just minutes earlier, Miller had led Ohio State on an 80-yard touchdown drive. But on the Wolverines’ bench, a mentality was taking hold."},{type:"text",value:"“We said as we came to the bench, ‘It’s not happening again,’ ” fifth-year senior defensive end Ryan Van Bergen said. “No way.”"},{type:"text",value:"Michigan forced fourth-and-6 in Ohio State territory. Miller dropped back to throw. Forty-five seconds remained."},{type:"text",value:"His pass bounced off Ohio State receiver Devin Smith and into Avery’s arms."},{type:"text",value:"From there, pandemonium."},{type:"text",value:"“When the interception came, it was kind of like, ‘There it is,’ ” fifth-year senior center David Molk said. “That’s what we needed to turn. That’s the momentum change that we needed to completely lock this game down. The defense stepped up. They did what they had to do when the time came.”"},{type:"text",value:"It had been 2,926 days since Michigan’s last win over Ohio State — a mark that is eclipsed now at 3,297 and counting."},{type:"text",value:"After Robinson took a knee to run out the clock for the final time, he tossed the ball into the air and when it fell back down, the team fell down around it, as if it was a grenade. By then, 107,601 fans were climbing onto the turf, creating a memory that wouldn’t soon be matched."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"failed-two-point-conversion-2013"},{type:"title",value:"Michigan’s 2013 failed two-point conversion changes the course of the rivalry"},{type:"author",value:"Daniel Dash"},{type:"description",value:"A failed two-point conversion attempt in 2013 prevented a struggling Michigan team from stunning the undefeated Buckeyes in Ann Arbor."},{type:"date",value:"November 30, 2013"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-3.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"<b></b>"},{type:"text",value:"One play. Two yards."},{type:"text",value:"In 2013, that’s what decided the Michigan football team’s game against undefeated Ohio State. The unranked Wolverines entered the Saturday after Thanksgiving having lost three of their last four games, but a win over the third-ranked Buckeyes presented an opportunity to erase the embarrassment of a 7-4 record."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State, on the other hand, was expected to waltz into Ann Arbor and deliver the knockout blow to Michigan’s season. The Buckeyes were vying for a spot in the national title game, and a rivalry win at the Big House was merely supposed to be another box to check."},{type:"text",value:"When Ohio State extended its lead to 35-21 in the late stages of the third quarter, it seemed the game would be exactly that. But Wolverines’ quarterback Devin Gardner refused to go away. The redshirt junior led back-to-back touchdown drives, tying the score at 35 with just five minutes to play. He finished 32-of-45 passing for 451 yards and accounted for five total touchdowns while playing through a foot injury that left him in a boot immediately afterwards."},{type:"text",value:"“He’s a kid,” Michigan coach Brady Hoke said. “He’s learning. I think he’s learning how to be a Michigan quarterback and I think that’s a daily thing. He’s beat up like everybody is, and when he was limping a little bit, I said, ‘I don’t want to see you limp. Every guy out here can limp. We’ve got to go play.’ He did that, and I’m proud of him.”"},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes answered Gardner’s comeback with a touchdown of their own. With 2:20 to play, Michigan had to march down the field to force overtime."},{type:"text",value:"Eleven plays, 84 yards and 1:48 later, the Wolverines got the touchdown they needed. But when Hoke asked for his seniors’ input on the sidelines, they had no interest in kicking a game-tying extra point. Instead, they opted to attempt a game-winning two-point conversion with just 32 seconds remaining."},{type:"text",value:"When Gardner zipped a pass to his right, however, it wasn’t his receiver who came up with the ball. Ohio State cornerback Tyvis Powell stepped in front of the pass and intercepted it, cementing the Buckeyes’ 42-41 victory."},{type:"text",value:"“That’s an instant classic,” Ohio State coach Urban Meyer said."},{type:"text",value:"Those two yards changed the course of the rivalry. Had Michigan converted the two-point attempt, it would’ve marked the Wolverines’ second win over the Buckeyes in three years. The win would’ve stained Meyer’s undefeated two-year run after landing in Columbus. But Powell’s interception gave Ohio State its ninth win in 10 years and maintained the Buckeyes’ dominance over their rival."},{type:"text",value:"Knocking off undefeated Ohio State would’ve given Michigan something to carry into 2014. It could’ve validated Hoke as the right guy for a sputtering program and given him something to sell on the recruiting trail. The two-point conversion could’ve changed the direction of the rivalry, though that may seem like nothing more than wishful thinking on the Wolverines’ behalf when considering the years that followed."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes have defeated Michigan by double digits in five of six meetings since their narrow 2013 win. They won the national title the next season and have claimed four Big Ten titles since, while the Wolverines have barely sniffed Indianapolis."},{type:"text",value:"Michigan limped into the 2014 season following a 17-point loss to Kansas State in the Buffalo Wild Wings Bowl. The Wolverines dropped three of their first four conference games, including a stunner against Rutgers. It became clear that Hoke’s program was rudderless, and the season culminated in his firing."},{type:"text",value:"His successor, Jim Harbaugh, is set to enter the 2020 iteration of the rivalry under similar circumstances. A struggling Michigan program will aim to knock off a top-five Ohio State team with an undefeated record."},{type:"text",value:"Whether or not this season’s edition of “The Game” comes down to two yards or isn’t even decided by two touchdowns remains to be seen."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"jim-harbaugh-2016"},{type:"title",value:"Inches changed the tides of Harbaugh’s Michigan reign in 2016 game"},{type:"author",value:"Ethan Sears"},{type:"description",value:"After the 2016 edition of The Game, Michigan coach Jim Harbaugh was upset about a double-overtime spot given to J.T. Barrett that helped decide the outcome. His program hasn’t come close to beating the Buckeyes since."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-4.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"Whenever and however the Jim Harbaugh era ends at Michigan, it will be looked back upon as the biggest what-if of his tenure. J.T. Barrett falling into tight end A.J. Alexander, the ball outstretched in his hands. Eleven Michigan players waving their arms to signal he didn’t cross the line; 11 Ohio State players pointing forwards to signal first down."},{type:"text",value:"And just minutes later, Buckeyes running back Curtis Samuel running into the end zone untouched to give Ohio State a 30-27, double-overtime win in the most memorable edition of The Game this decade."},{type:"text",value:"“I am bitterly disappointed with the officiating today,” Michigan coach Jim Harbaugh said. “That spot.”"},{type:"text",value:"He held his hands apart to show how short he thought Barrett was. He asked reporters what they thought. He got fined $10,000 by the Big Ten the following Monday for comments on the officiating that went on to include gripes about pass interference calls and an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty incurred after he threw his play card and slammed his headset in the third quarter."},{type:"text",value:"“We won the game,” Ohio State coach Urban Meyer said, and indeed, history has no sympathy for Harbaugh’s complaints."},{type:"text",value:"The 2016 team was undoubtedly Harbaugh’s best thus far at Michigan, coming into The Game ranked third in the country and in control of its own destiny for a College Football Playoff spot. Nonetheless, it couldn’t take down Ohio State, which was ranked second and went on to make the Playoff."},{type:"text",value:"Despite the controversy over the spot, the Wolverines had plenty of opportunities to avoid overtime altogether. Nursing a shoulder injury, quarterback Wilton Speight committed two key turnovers — a second-quarter pick six and a third-quarter fumble on Ohio State’s one-yard line. Michigan led by as much as 17-7, with Don Brown’s defense holding the Buckeyes to 330 total yards, but it wasn’t enough."},{type:"text",value:"A second Speight interception allowed Ohio State to cut the lead to three and Barrett led the Buckeyes to a game-tying drive at the end of regulation, with Tyler Durbin kicking a 23-yard field goal."},{type:"text",value:"In the three editions of The Game since, the Wolverines have never come as close to winning. And in the last two years, their defense hasn’t been close to the same level — in 2018 and 2019, Ohio State’s offensive yardage totals were 567 and 577, respectively."},{type:"text",value:"At the time, it seemed to represent a new era for the rivalry, and maybe a new 10-year war between Harbaugh and Meyer. Michigan had lost, but proven it could play on equal footing with its greatest rival in their home stadium."},{type:"text",value:"With the glint of perspective, even that most optimistic of takeaways proved completely wrong. Meyer retired after once again keeping Michigan from a College Football Playoff berth in the Horseshoe in 2018. Harbaugh finds himself on the hot seat heading into this year’s game. The Wolverines haven’t been competitive with Ohio State since then, and few expect them to be in 2020."},{type:"text",value:"If that spot is different, maybe everything else is, too. Maybe Michigan wins the Big Ten, makes the College Football Playoff, keeps recruiting at a top-five level nationally and a newly-renewed 10-year war comes to fruition. Maybe this rivalry is competitive, instead of a yearly funeral procession to the Wolverines’ season."},{type:"text",value:"But maybes will do no solace to Harbaugh, nor to Michigan’s program."}]}],lantern:[{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"ohio-states-success"},{type:"title",value:"Ohio State’s success with and without breakout running backs"},{type:"author",value:"Keaton Maisano"},{type:"description",value:"Ohio State has dominated Michigan over the past decade, and that dominance can largely be linked to the Buckeyes’ success on the ground."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2019/11/edit-8059.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-junior running back J.K. Dobbins (2) runs the ball down the field to score a touchdown during the second half of the game against Michigan at Michigan Stadium Nov. 30. Ohio State won 56-27. Credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State has dominated Michigan over the past decade, and that dominance can largely be linked to the Buckeyes’ success on the ground."},{type:"text",value:"Over the last 10 meetings between the rivals, Ohio State running backs have rushed for more than 100 yards on seven occasions. In many of these cases, the Buckeyes employed elite talent at the running back position with six of the last seven feature backs entering The Game with more than 1,000 yards rushing on the season."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State running backs failed to eclipse 1,000 rushing yards prior to the Michigan game from 2010-12. Over the three year stretch, the Buckeyes went 2-1 against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"In the two victories, Ohio State’s No. 1 running back dashed for 175 yards in 2010 and 146 yards in 2012."},{type:"text",value:"In the lone loss in 2011, then-redshirt senior running back Dan Herron was held to 37 yards and a touchdown on 15 carries. Then-freshman quarterback Braxton Miller would add 100 yards and a touchdown on the ground, but the Buckeyes would fall 40-34."},{type:"text",value:"In his second season as the feature back, then-senior Carlos Hyde led the shift from a quarterback-centric running game by becoming the first Buckeye running back in the decade to enter The Game with more than 1,000 yards on the season."},{type:"text",value:"Hyde also became the first Ohio State running back to rush for more than 200 yards in The Game — tallying the highest total in the history of the rivalry with 226 yards in the thrilling 42-41 win over the Wolverines in 2013."},{type:"text",value:"Over the next four seasons, Buckeye running backs followed Hyde’s lead, each entering The Game with more than 1,000 yards. In their rivalry matchups, three of the four Ohio State running backs were able to eclipse 100 yards — including a 214-yard, two-touchdown performance from then-junior Ezekiel Elliott in 2015."},{type:"text",value:"Elliott had one of the more productive runs as the No. 1 back in The Game. In two games, Elliott rushed for 335 yards and four touchdowns and earned two pairs of gold pants."},{type:"text",value:"In 2016, No. 2 Ohio State played host to No. 3 Michigan. Then-freshman running back Mike Weber entered the game as Ohio State’s leading rusher with 1,046 yards, but the Michigan native was held mostly in check — finishing the game with 26 rushing yards and a touchdown on 11 carries."},{type:"text",value:"Like previous seasons, Ohio State leaned on the quarterback position for an added element to the rushing attack. Then-redshirt junior quarterback J.T. Barrett would obtain 125 yards and a touchdown on 30 carries."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State’s 30-27 win in overtime would be stamped off a touchdown run from then-junior running back Curtis Samuel, who finished the game with 54 rushing yards."},{type:"text",value:"Running back J.K. Dobbins’ arrival in 2017 marked the transition to the next running back at Ohio State."},{type:"text",value:"His freshman campaign included 1,403 rushing yards and a performance against Michigan in which he eclipsed 100 yards and found the end zone."},{type:"text",value:"The 2018 season saw an unusual shift for the Buckeyes. Leaning on a passing attack led by then-redshirt sophomore Dwayne Haskins, Ohio State entered the Michigan game without a running back eclipsing 1,000 yards for the first time since 2012."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes would use 396 passing yards from Haskins to down Michigan 62-39. Dobbins would finish with 46 yards on 12 carries while Weber would lead the team with 96 yards on 13 carries."},{type:"text",value:"Dobbins would break through the following year with a record-setting season."},{type:"text",value:"The then-junior running back would amass 1,446 yards and 15 touchdowns entering the Michigan game, and he would add 211 yards and four touchdowns against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"Dobbins would go on to break the Ohio State single-season rushing record — previously held by Eddie George. He would finish the season with 2,003 rushing yards and 21 touchdowns on the ground."},{type:"text",value:"In terms of total yards, Hyde produced the most in his appearances in the rivalry with 372 while Dobbins was able to find the end zone the most — finishing with five touchdowns in his three appearances. Elliott led the way in yards per attempt, gathering an average of 7.13 yards on each carry in his two performances."},{type:"text",value:"Although 2018 served as an outlier, the path to success against Michigan the past decade has been on the ground — not through the air."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"the-longest-win-streaks"},{type:"title",value:"The longest winning streaks in the history of The Game"},{type:"author",value:"Jack Emerson"},{type:"description",value:"As the Buckeyes look to tie the series-longest nine-game winning streak Dec. 12, here’s an in-depth look back at some of the longest winning streaks in the rivalry."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2019/11/edit-7037.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-sophomore wide receiver Chris Olave (17) celebrates after scoring a touchdown during the first half of the game against Michigan at Michigan Stadium Nov. 30. Ohio State won 56-27. Credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Since 2012, Ohio State has been in the midst of one of the longest winning streaks in the history of its illustrious rivalry with Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"As the Buckeyes look to tie the series-longest nine-game winning streak Dec. 12, here’s an in-depth look back at some of the longest winning streaks in the rivalry."},{type:"<b>1901-09",value:"Michigan wins nine straight</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b></b>"},{type:"text",value:"From Ohio State and Michigan’s first meeting in 1897 to 1918, the Buckeyes failed to beat their rival to the north. The Wolverines amassed a 12-0-2 record against the Buckeyes in that span — including a rivalry-best nine straight wins from 1901-09."},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines kick-started the run with a 21-0 win over the Buckeyes in 1901."},{type:"text",value:"A year later, Michigan won by the greatest margin of victory in the rivalry’s history with a dominating 86-0 victory over Ohio State in Ann Arbor. It is believed that on the train back to Columbus following Ohio State’s catastrophic defeat, then-freshman defensive end and glee club member Fred Cornell wrote the lyrics to “Carmen Ohio” — marking the beginning of a classic Ohio State tradition."},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines continued their dominance over the early stages of the rivalry, especially on the defensive end, as the Buckeyes failed to score more than six points in each matchup during the nine-year run. Ohio State was shut out in six of the nine losses."},{type:"text",value:"Michigan outscored Ohio State 285-18 during the record winning streak."},{type:"<b>2012-19",value:"Ohio State wins eight straight</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Over the eight-year stretch, each team has transitioned to a new head coach, but the results have stayed the same, with Ohio State ahead and Michigan trailing behind."},{type:"text",value:"Although Brady Hoke was able to begin his tenure with a win over Ohio State in 2011, he failed to beat the Buckeyes in each of his next three attempts. 2012 not only marked the beginning of the end for Hoke, but it began the seven-year dominance of Urban Meyer in the rivalry."},{type:"text",value:"Meyer would end all seven of his regular seasons at Ohio State with a win over Michigan. The biggest matchup under his watch would occur in 2016 when he led the No. 2 Buckeyes over No. 3 Michigan in an overtime thriller to earn a spot in the College Football Playoff."},{type:"text",value:"Even with the hiring of Jim Harbaugh in December of 2014, the Buckeyes continued to dominate the series."},{type:"text",value:"Meyer’s departure at the end of the 2018 season appeared to be an opportunity for Harbaugh to earn his first victory over the Buckeyes, but first-year head coach Ryan Day was able to take his No. 1 Ohio State team into Michigan Stadium and emphatically extend the streak to eight games with a 56-27 win."},{type:"<b>2004-10*",value:"Ohio State wins seven* straight </b>"},{type:"text",value:"In 2001, the Buckeyes hired head coach Jim Tressel, who brought back the emphasis toward the rivalry between the two programs."},{type:"text",value:"Tressel saw his greatest success from 2004-10, winning seven straight games against Ohio State’s heated rival."},{type:"text",value:"The streak began when the Buckeyes pulled off a major upset at home against the No. 7 Wolverines, winning 37-21. Then-redshirt junior quarterback Troy Smith led Ohio State, throwing for 241 yards and 2 touchdowns while adding 145 yards and a touchdown on the ground."},{type:"text",value:"After earning another win in 2005, the Buckeyes entered the 2006 matchup as the No. 1 team in the country. Michigan entered the game as No. 2, creating an all-time great atmosphere in the rivalry."},{type:"text",value:"The game lived up to the hype — being dubbed “The Game of the Century” — Tressel earned his third straight win against the Wolverines and Smith added to his Heisman Trophy resume with an all-time performance."},{type:"text",value:"Tressel would not lose to Michigan in his Ohio State career again prior to his abrupt departure in 2010, however the 2010 win was vacated by the NCAA."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"ohio-state-dominance"},{type:"title",value:"Ohio State dominance transcends the scoreboard"},{type:"author",value:"Keaton Maisano and Jack Emerson"},{type:"description",value:"Ohio State has had success against Michigan throughout the past decade and the dominance has transitioned to the NFL draft."},{type:"date",value:"December 1st"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2019/11/edit-7982.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-junior defensive end Chase Young (2) attempts to evade Michigan graduate offensive lineman Jon Runyan (75) during the second half of the game at Michigan Stadium Nov. 30. Ohio State won 56-27. Credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State has dominated Michigan over the past decade and the dominance has been evident in the early picks in the NFL drafts."},{type:"text",value:"Since 2016, Ohio State has had six players drafted in the top-five picks of the NFL draft — the most of any program in that time span. The Wolverines, on the other hand, have not had a top-five selection since 2008 when offensive tackle Jake Long was taken first overall."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State’s highly touted NFL prospects left their mark on the rivalry’s history books with some great performances in the yearly matchup."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2016 — No. 3: Joey Bosa (11 tackles, 4.5 tackles for loss, 3.5 sacks, 1 interception, 1 forced fumble)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The older Bosa brother never wasted an opportunity to have an impact game against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"In three career games against the Wolverines, Bosa recorded at least one tackle, 0.5 tackles for loss and 0.5 sacks in each of his appearances in The Game."},{type:"text",value:"Bosa’s best performance came in his final regular season game as a Buckeye in 2015 with Bosa collecting three tackles, one tackle for loss, a sack, an interception and a forced fumble in Ohio State’s 42-13 win over Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"In the 2016 NFL draft, Bosa became the first Buckeye drafted in the top five since linebacker A.J. Hawk was selected No. 5 by the Packers in 2006. Bosa was selected No. 3 overall by the then-San Diego Chargers."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2016 — No. 4: Ezekiel Elliott (47 carries, 335 rushing yards, 4 touchdowns)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The Dallas Cowboys used the pick after Bosa on another Buckeye, this time on the offensive side of the ball."},{type:"text",value:"Running back Ezekiel Elliott played a crucial role in Ohio State’s victories over Michigan in 2014 and 2015."},{type:"text",value:"Elliott pieced together a 121-yard performance in his rivalry debut in 2014, adding two touchdowns through the ground."},{type:"text",value:"A year later, Elliott exploded for 214 yards and two touchdowns against the Wolverines, leading the Buckeyes to their fourth-straight victory over their rival."},{type:"text",value:"Elliott became the first running back picked in the top five since former Alabama running back Trent Richardson was selected No. 3 by the Cleveland Browns in 2012."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2018 — No. 4: Denzel Ward (11 tackles, 3 pass deflections)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"In two appearances in The Game, Ward kept up his lockdown distinction in his battles with the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"In his rivalry debut in 2016, Ward collected three tackles and broke up a pass."},{type:"text",value:"In his next bout with the Wolverines, Ward had a top-tier performance in the backend of the Ohio State defense. Ward finished with a team-high eight tackles and two pass breakups."},{type:"text",value:"Ward was selected by the Cleveland Browns with the No. 4 pick in the 2018 draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2019 — No. 2: Nick Bosa (7 tackles, 2 sacks)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"A few years after Joey Bosa’s reign of terror on the Ohio State defensive line, his younger brother, Nick, appeared to be another threat to Michigan’s offense."},{type:"text",value:"Nick Bosa recorded a sack in his first career bout with the Wolverines in 2016 along with two tackles."},{type:"text",value:"In 2017, the younger Bosa brother improved on his performance from a year prior, adding five tackles alongside a sack."},{type:"text",value:"In the 2019 NFL draft, Nick Bosa was selected one pick ahead of his older brother, joining his brother professionally in California. Bosa joined the talented defensive line corps of the San Francisco 49ers."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2020 — No. 2: Chase Young (2 tackles, 1 tackle for loss, 1 pass deflection)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Then-junior defensive end Chase Young had high expectations heading into his final matchup against Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Although he did not tally a tackle — let alone a sack — Young’s production was largely diminished by the double teams he received throughout the game."},{type:"text",value:"As a team, the Buckeyes recorded two sacks to go along with eight tackles for loss."},{type:"text",value:"In his two games played, Young would tally two tackles, a tackle for loss and a pass deflection against Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Young was taken No. 2 overall by the Washington Football Team in the 2020 NFL draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2020 — No. 3: Jeff Okudah (4 tackles, 2 pass deflections)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Two years after Ward left for the NFL, then-junior Jeff Okudah was the next highly-touted corner back to occupy Ohio State’s secondary."},{type:"text",value:"In two career games against the Wolverines, Okudah recorded four tackles and was in on a pair of pass deflections. In 2019, Okudah would be part of a secondary that struggled heavily in the first half — allowing 250 passing yards in the first half."},{type:"text",value:"However, Okudah and the secondary would stifle Michigan’s passing attack in the second half and hold the Wolverines to only 65 passing yards."},{type:"text",value:"Okudah was drafted by the Detroit Lions with the No. 3 overall pick in the 2020 NFL draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>*Career Stats vs. Michigan</b>"}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"ohio-passing-and-receiving"},{type:"title",value:"Ohio State’s top passing and receiving games in The Game’s history"},{type:"author",value:"Keaton Maisano and Jack Emerson"},{type:"description",value:"A look at Ohio State’s top individual passing and receiving games against Michigan."},{type:"date",value:"December 1st"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2018/11/IMG_0379-1a1zj13.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-redshirt sophomore quarterback Dwayne Haskins (7) looks to pass the ball during the second half of the game against Michigan on Nov. 24. Ohio State won 62-39. credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Throughout the history of The Game, Ohio State and Michigan have largely slugged it out in the trenches and on the ground, but there have been plenty of iconic passing and receiving displays in the rivalry."},{type:"<b>Passing",value:"</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 1: Dwayne Haskins (2018) — 396 yards, 6 TDs, 0 INTs, 20/31</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 62-39</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The 2018 iteration of The Game brought a top-ranked Michigan defense to Ohio Stadium to square off with Ohio State’s potent passing attack."},{type:"text",value:"In what was expected to be Michigan head coach Jim Harbaugh’s first career win against Ohio State, then-redshirt sophomore quarterback Dwayne Haskins spoiled his day with an all-time great performance."},{type:"text",value:"Haskins threw for nearly 400 yards and added six touchdowns while helping the Buckeyes to their highest scoring total in the rivalry’s history — 62 points."},{type:"text",value:"Haskins’ 396 yards and six touchdown passes both are Ohio State records in their yearly matchup with the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"The New Jersey native would go on to finish the season with Big Ten records in both yards and touchdowns with 4,831 and 50, respectively."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 2: Joe Germaine (1998) — 330 yards, 3 TDs, 0 INTs, 16/28</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 31-16</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Then-senior quarterback Joe Germaine entered the 1998 game with a wealth of receiving talent around him and tremendous amount of pressure after failing to produce a win in his first two career starts against Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Germaine would not succumb to the pressure and had one of the best performances in his Buckeye career against the then-No 11 Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"The Colorado native outdueled Michigan quarterback Tom Brady, throwing for a then-Ohio State rivalry record 330 yards and three touchdowns in the 31-16 triumph over the Wolverines in Columbus."},{type:"text",value:"Germaine’s efforts helped former Buckeye coach John Cooper earn his second, and final, career win against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"Germaine finished his senior season with 3,330 yards and 25 touchdowns while leading the Buckeyes to a Sugar Bowl victory."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 3: Troy Smith (2006) — 316 yards, 4 TDs, 1 INT, 29/41</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 42-39 </b>"},{type:"text",value:"“The Game of the Century” largely landed on the shoulders of Ohio State’s Heisman-candidate and then-redshirt senior quarterback Troy Smith."},{type:"text",value:"Smith stepped up in a big way in the matchup between the two top-ranked teams in the country, throwing for more than 300 yards and connecting on four touchdown passes while completing just more than 70 percent of his passes."},{type:"text",value:"The 42-39 win allowed the Buckeyes to hold the top spot in the country and earn an opportunity to play in the BCS National Championship game. Ohio State would not prevail in the title game, falling to Florida 41-14."},{type:"text",value:"Smith would go on to earn the highest individual honor in college football — the Heisman Trophy — with a stat line of 2,542 passing yards and 30 touchdowns."},{type:"<b>Receiving",value:"</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 1 David Boston (1998) — 10 catches, 217 yards, 2 TDs</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 31-16</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Then-junior wide receiver David Boston had a special year in 1998, but possibly the highlight of his season came in a late November matchup with Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Boston would put together a performance better than any Ohio State wide receiver before him when playing Michigan, and his 217 receiving yards have yet to be topped. The Texas native hauled in 10 catches and two touchdowns in his climb above the 200-yard mark."},{type:"text",value:"His performance is still No. 4 in most receiving yards by an Ohio State receiver in a single game, and Boston sits at No. 2 for most receiving yards in an Ohio State career."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes would win the game 31-16 and Boston would finish the season with a school-record 1,435 receiving yards and 13 touchdowns."},{type:"text",value:"Boston would be selected No. 8 overall by the Arizona Cardinals in the 1999 NFL draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 2 Paris Campbell (2018) — 6 catches, 192 yards, 2 TDs</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 62-39</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines had no answer for then-senior wide receiver Paris Campbell’s speed in 2018."},{type:"text",value:"Campbell would save his best performance for his last game at Ohio Stadium when the Buckeyes were able to down Michigan 62-39."},{type:"text",value:"Not only would the Ohio native tally a career-high 192 receiving yards, but he would dash for the longest play of his career when he took a touch pass 78 yards to the endzone."},{type:"text",value:"Campbell would finish the game with a pair of touchdowns. He would finish his senior season with 1,063 receiving yards to go along with 12 touchdowns."},{type:"text",value:"The second-round selection in the 2019 NFL draft is just one of five players to eclipse the 1,000-yard receiving mark in a single season at Ohio State."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 3 Michael Jenkins (2003)* — 9 catches, 132 yards, 0 TD</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>*Santonio Holmes (2003) — 8 catches, 121 yards, 2 TDs</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State lost 35-21</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes would turn to the air in an attempt to beat the Wolverines in 2003, and although two Ohio State receivers were able to put on impressive performances, it was not enough to prevent former head coach Jim Tressel from dropping his first — and only — game to Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Then-junior wide receiver Michael Jenkins would provide the Buckeyes with a game-high 132 receiving yards. The national champion would also bring in nine catches but fail to see any result in six points."},{type:"text",value:"Jenkins was not alone in his ability to punish the Wolverine secondary, as then-redshirt freshman wide receiver Santonio Holmes added another eight catches for 121 yards."},{type:"text",value:"Unlike Jenkins, Holmes was able to turn two of his catches into touchdowns."},{type:"text",value:"The game still stands as the only instance in which two Ohio State teammates each topped 100 receiving yards against Michigan."}]}]};